*********************************
DeepSeek=E2=80=99s Lessons for Chinese AI
*********************************

I apologize for adding yet another DeepSeek video to your video queue. Duri=
ng a trip to Tokyo last year, I was told that DeepSeek was the real deal. A=
 cracked team, and perhaps the only ones of significance in China. Since th=
en, I have annoyed the guys on Transistor Radio - our podcast with Dylan Pa=
tel and Doug O'Laughlin - into talking about it. Though there was nothing m=
uch to be said. In December 2024, DeepSeek released their V3 base model, wh=
ich had impressive efficiency. A few people in AI were impressed. Then on J=
anuary 22nd 2025, DeepSeek released their reasoning model, R1, which works =
kind of like OpenAI's o1 and o3 models. It takes extra compute time to "thi=
nk" up a better answer. R1's release kicked everything off. The next day, t=
he New York Times published an article on it, but focused mostly on the ear=
lier V3's training costs:

The Chinese engineers said they needed only about $6 million in raw computi=
ng power to build their new system. That is about 10 times less than the te=
ch giant Meta spent building its latest A.I. technology.

The article seems to be saying that you don't need anywhere as many chips a=
s previously thought for leading edge AI. A message that other large media =
and smaller influencers amplified. Then on Saturday, the 25th, CNBC publish=
ed a 40 minute YouTube video that blew up. As of this writing, it has nearl=
y 5 million views. I'm very jealous. All this led to a massive move down fo=
r tech and semiconductor markets on Monday, losing a trillion dollars of ma=
rket value. Nvidia lost 17% or $600 billion. The biggest single day loss in=
 history. There was a massive online frenzy. CEOs and AI influencers alike =
posted soothing words. People were suddenly becoming experts on Jevon's Par=
adox and all that. I wasn't able to cover any of this as it happened becaus=
e it happened during the New Year holiday in Taiwan, so I was spending time=
 with family. Immaculate timing, guys. So I missed that early rush, but I w=
rote up a few things anyway. DeepSeek's leadership believes they have the w=
ay forward for Chinese AI. But does their approach scale? And what does it =
say about the Chinese AI industry as a whole? For today's video, a few disc=
ombobulated thoughts on DeepSeek.

-----------------------------
Limitations Breed Innovations
-----------------------------

I am not going to try to explain in detail what is so special about these n=
ew DeepSeek models. Oh boy, there are so many of those videos out there. Th=
is is what I=E2=80=99ll say. The DeepSeek models pull out all the tricks in=
 the book - including several new tricks of their own - to create a model t=
hat uses significantly less compute to both train and inference. Some of th=
ese innovations involve "stealing" data from larger models like GPT-4 and C=
laude via distillation. There are issues of perceived fairness with such a =
technique but I reckon it is ultimately unavoidable. Another innovation was=
 using 8-bit floating point numbers over industry standard 32-bit floating =
point numbers. There is also an interesting thing done with a mixture of ex=
perts structure. Ben points out in his FAQ over at Stratechery that many su=
ch innovations can be traced to the limitations of Nvidia's China-specific =
hardware. So in one way, you can say that the terror case is playing out. W=
e imposed restrictions on the Chinese, and the Chinese innovated something =
new to evade those restrictions. Like a bacteria growing resistant to a dos=
e of antibiotics.

-----------------
What DeepSeek Saw
-----------------

It is pretty nifty how DeepSeek assembled them all into one slim model - ju=
st look at OpenAI's model selector menu to see how hard that is. But I shou=
ld point out that most of these tricks are known or implemented in earlier =
models by other companies. For example, Mistral has been using Mixture of E=
xperts since at least December 2023. But there is one apparent insight abou=
t R1 that caught my eye. Trust me I am no expert. But from what I can disce=
rn, DeepSeek managed to endow R1-zero with chain-of-thought and reasoning b=
ehaviors without having to insert a human into the loop. This approach took=
 balls. It is a simple idea which people have tried before only to end in f=
ailure. So DeepSeek not only noticed that it works now for a variety of rea=
sons, but also decided to throw big-model resources behind it. There is ano=
ther thing. I am intrigued by DeepSeek founder and head Liang Wenfeng's (=
=E6=A2=81=E6=96=87=E9=94=8B) explanation in an interview about how DeepSeek=
's memory-saving Multi-Head Latent architecture came about.

After summarizing some mainstream evolutionary trends of the attention mech=
anism, [the DeepSeek employee behind MLA] just thought to design an alterna=
tive. However, turning the idea into reality was a lengthy process. We form=
ed a team specifically for this and spent months getting it to work

Imagine what it might take to spend months on such a task, based on a resea=
rcher's hunch. That takes a special team in my opinion, and Liang confirms =
this.

---------------------------
The Organization of Talents
---------------------------

DeepSeek's moat, as Liang says, is not its current innovations but a team c=
apable of generating innovations anew. Liang has an interest in team develo=
pment. He wrote the preface to the Chinese language version of Gregory Zuck=
erman's biography of Jim Simons and Renaissance Technologies: "The Man Who =
Solved the Market". His book preface marks his interest in building lasting=
, successful teams. In it, he wrote:

What kind of characteristics and opportunities made Simons a historical out=
lier? How do you build and manage an outstanding team that remains undefeat=
ed for more than 30 years? ... Readers can find answers in this book.

And going to the second of Liang's two 36Kr interviews - basically the only=
 such interviews on the web - what most people have glommed onto were his q=
uotes about the superiority of the open source approach compared to closed =
source approaches. But most of the interview actually focused on how China =
can better surface innovation, as well as the latent strengths of the Chine=
se people. Liang is trying to rally other Chinese to make "hard" innovation=
s like they do and explains how his team does it. After reading the intervi=
ews, I get the sense that DeepSeek is a very non-Chinese company. Its found=
er especially so. Such a contrarian structure lets it tap (supposedly) the =
very best of what Chinese talents can offer in leading edge software develo=
pment.

-------------------------------------------------
Software Development with Chinese Characteristics
-------------------------------------------------

To give you a sense of where I am driving at here, I think I need to give s=
ome background on how top-level Chinese software companies like ByteDance a=
nd PinDuoDuo work. China has plenty of "normal" software companies, no diff=
erent structurally from those in the United States. Want to make that clear=
. But China's startup league leaders are distinct, with fascinating organiz=
ations. Their dev teams are huge, sometimes dozens or even hundreds of peop=
le. And only roughly half of those team members are developers. The other h=
alf seems to be mostly "operations staff". Which, as best as I can tell, is=
 a generic word for labor-heavy tasks. Makes sense considering the low labo=
r cost there. Like they rely on big quality assurance teams to test code be=
fore it goes out. Which is generally not the case in the US, where it seems=
 like developers are expected to QA their own code. The way these big Chine=
se companies manage such big teams is with top-down management. So you have=
 these meetings with 20-30 plus people where marching orders are basically =
broadcast to them. Staff like AI Researchers are guided by OKRs and KPIs, w=
ritten every quarter by their managers. OKRs often cover the improvement of=
 a model as well as its implementation through 2-3 features to be released =
that quarter. ByteDance has a big leaderboard that refreshes every so often=
. And when one of their Doubao models cannot keep up with the other top mod=
els in China then the anxiety within that particular LLM team is palpable. =
Moreover, information sharing with the outside world has been closed off. W=
ithin ByteDance, Alibaba and the other major Chinese AI startups - nickname=
d the Six Little AI Dragons of China - there is a freeze on publishing. Sam=
e as in the United States. These Chinese software practices are obviously c=
herry-picked. But I am trying to make a point about DeepSeek. Small teams w=
ith little hierarchy or separation, flexibly going wherever their passion t=
akes them. Workers allowed to publish what they learn, with their names att=
ached to it. And the time, resources, and balls to go forth into the abyss =
to chase long term insights. DeepSeek really does seem to buck convention i=
n China.

------------------
DeepSeek, the Team
------------------

In both 36Kr interviews, Liang talks about his focus on hiring for ability.=
 In his first interview, he talks about how he first hired his fund's sales=
 team and their struggles during their early development:

For example, our top two salespeople were outsiders =E2=80=94 one came from=
 exporting German machinery, and the other wrote backend code at a securiti=
es firm. When they entered this field, they had no experience, no resources=
, and no prior connections.

In fact, our sales team achieved nothing in their first year, and it was on=
ly in the second year that they started to see some results. But our evalua=
tion standards are quite different from those of most companies. We don=E2=
=80=99t have KPIs or so-called quotas.

Imagine what patience it might take for a company in China, the US, or anyw=
here to tolerate a whole year of nonperformance. Interestingly, Liang menti=
ons that the DeepSeek V2 team does not have a sea turtle, as in overseas-tr=
ained Chinese. Noticeable since Chinese startups like to brag that their em=
ployees are elites with degrees from places like Harvard. That being said. =
DeepSeek does seem like to hire from Peking and Tsinghua Universities - not=
 exactly China's DeVry. They tend to shy away from hiring famous people. An=
 online interview with an unnamed DeepSeek headhunter mentioned the company=
's preference not to hire people who have already been successful, saying:

Those who have been successful in the past have already achieved success; t=
hey carry the burden of not being allowed to fail. It=E2=80=99s better to l=
eave innovation to newcomers.

--------------------
Will DeepSeek Scale?
--------------------

It does seem like Chinese tech companies are somewhat buying the pitch. Byt=
eDance for example has this new "SEED Edge" team, a team stocked with highl=
y paid cracked researchers empowered with over half of the company's margin=
al GPU compute. The goal is to do research for the =E2=80=9Clong term=E2=80=
=9D. Others are doing similarly. But I doubt these Chinese tech giants can =
entirely pivot to operating like how DeepSeek does. It is not like what the=
y are doing isn=E2=80=99t working for them. Moreover, I question whether De=
epSeek itself can maintain its old ways going forward. Why? Well first, Dee=
pSeek has now gone mainstream. All the worldwide publicity has pushed its c=
hat app to the number one spot in many countries around the world - somethi=
ng Anthropic was never able to do for Claude. It would behoove DeepSeek's m=
anagement not to take advantage of this hype. In his appearance in the Lex =
Fridman podcast, Dylan Patel mentioned offhandedly that DeepSeek is now try=
ing to raise a round. I think they are going to go head to head with OpenAI=
 in the prosumer chatbot market. Such a pathway means scaling up - adding p=
roduct managers, marketing, sales, and doing all the little things OpenAI d=
id to become a "real" company. And that inevitably will dilute their unique=
 research culture. Second, closing a gap always feels fast. As DeepSeek ent=
ers uncharted territory, gains become harder to grasp. There is precedent f=
or this. Just look at Anthropic, a small team that rapidly caught up to Ope=
nAI but has since struggled to move past them. Here is another precedent. D=
eepSeek's predecessor hedge fund High Flyer boomed thanks to an AI system f=
irst developed in 2015. It worked well until 2021, when returns started to =
lag due to higher assets under management and more intense competition. It =
eventually caused Liang and management to apologize to customers through We=
Chat at the end of 2021. This unusual event was covered in the Wall Street =
Journal. A year later in 2023, they founded DeepSeek. Third. There are tale=
nt issues. If I was running an AI team in China, I=E2=80=99d be giving each=
 of those DeepSeek employees offers that even their passions can't refuse. =
It is already happening. In late December 2024, before all the hysteria, Ch=
inese media reported that Xiaomi's founder Lei Jun personally recruited Luo=
 Fuli (=E7=BE=85=E7=A6=8F=E8=8E=89), one of the "genius girls" behind DeepS=
eek V2, with a $1.3 million salary to run their LLM team. Replacing such ta=
lents will be challenging. I suppose that's fine though in the end. There w=
ill be more. China graduates an estimated Croatia or Panama's worth of STEM=
 graduates each year: 4 to 5 million. One thing DeepSeek will do I feel is =
lift the stigma of a purely domestic hire.

-----
Chips
-----

One key limiter for DeepSeek's team and all others will be chips. Liang say=
s so in his second 36Kr interview:

Money has never been the problem for us; bans on shipments of advanced chip=
s are the problem.

Did anyone see that DeepSeek's hosted models are running inference on Huawe=
i Ascend 910C hardware? It makes perfect sense that China's leading AI lab =
work with China's best hardware engineering company. The DeepSeek kerfuffle=
 will motivate the American government to further tighten the export of Nvi=
dia chips. Even if all of DeepSeek's Nvidia chips are "kosher", it looks to=
 me that they will get cut off. And Nvidia's China revenue will go to zero =
in the foreseeable future. Thusly, China's AI companies will have no choice=
 but to turn to Huawei, whose Ascend accelerators are very good. This in tu=
rn will strengthen the Huawei-SMIC industrial complex, ramping up their sem=
iconductor proficiency. It has been said that Google held a hardware-derive=
d cost advantage because of their TPU ecosystem. Imagine Chinese AI compani=
es possessing similar TPU-like advantages over their American cohorts. It w=
ould be beneficial for the Americans to have access to the most FLOPs per d=
ollar they can possibly get.

----------
Conclusion
----------

So yeah, I don=E2=80=99t think DeepSeek's rather un-Chinese-like approach s=
cales. They seem more like an 1 of 1. But it doesn't have to. Popular senti=
ment in the West is that the US is dominant in software, maybe unassailably=
 so. This is wrong. China is one of the few countries with a world-competit=
ive software industry. They are far better at it than Americans think. And =
specifically within AI, the Chinese are world beaters in face recognition, =
machine vision and other fields. We bring over bunches of Chinese to the US=
 to write our code. Why should we think that they can=E2=80=99t catch up an=
d FAST? With regards to LLM development, the Chinese see themselves in a wa=
r situation. It is like their EV industry during the mid to late 2010s, wit=
h a multitude of teams irresponsibly spending their way to the top. I think=
 the American AI labs have too much confidence in their massive capital exp=
enditure numbers, their perceived lead in productization, and their cozines=
s with government. I urge them to push harder. DeepSeek was the first Chine=
se lab to come out of left field, but it won't be the last.

